out_desc_tool: The Number Concept Test measured the development of the children's understanding of number. The Number Concepts Test (19 items) was developed to test nine components of number  rote counting, rational counting or enumeration, subitizing, cardinal number, ordinal number, less than/greater than, one-to-one correspondence, con- servation of number, and part-part-whole.

out_desc_tool: The evaluation was conducted at two level - 1. to assess the quality of 'readiness' attained for number work in terms of the specified concepts and cognitive skills. 2. to assess the quality of acquisition of number concept as an outcome of the expected 'superior' level of readiness. The tools/tests for evaluation were again framed at two levels - "concrete' and 'abstract'. The concrete testing situation involved manipulation of concrete objects from the environment. The 'abstract' evaluation was done through specially prepared worksheets. The 'concrete' testing situation was resorted to only if the child was not able to perform through the worksheets. The scores were accordingly assigned i.e. 2 for correct response at the 'abstract' level, 1 for 'concrete' level and '0' for incorrect response.

The tools/tests for evaluation were again framed at two levels - "concrete' and 'abstract'. The concrete testing situation involved manipulation of concrete objects from the environment. The 'abstract' evaluation was done through specially prepared worksheets. The 'concrete' testing situation was resorted to only if the child was not able to perform through the worksheets. The scores were accordingly assigned i.e. 2 for correct response at the 'abstract' level, 1 for 'concrete' level and '0' for incorrect response.

out_desc_tool: This study utilized the first 28 problems of the WoodcockJohnson III Applied Problems (quantitative) scale. This scale starts with, “Show me just one finger,” and proceeds through problems such as, “If you took three of these balloons away how many would be left?” to “How much money is this?” The problems refer to pictures of the objects in question. Testing is terminated when a child misses four consecutive problems.

out_desc_tool: This test, which is designed for children age 3 years 0 months to 8 years 11 months, assesses formal (e.g., numeral literacy) and informal (e.g., relative magnitude) mathematics abilities. Examples of questions primarily targeted for ages 4 and 5 years include asking children to verbally count from 1 to 10, to hold up four ﬁngers, to state which number (word) comes after a single-digit number, to choose the numerically larger of the two Arabic numbers, and to solve simple single-digit addition and subtraction word problems.

out_desc_tool: These three scales, derived from the item bank of the ‘Early Mathematical Competence Test [Utrechtse Getalbegrip Toets] (UGT) (Van Luit et al., 1994), can be used to select young children with a possible developmental lag in early mathematical compe- tence. The scales consist of eight parts  Concepts of comparison, Classiﬁca- tion, Correspondence, Seriation, Using counting words, Structured counting, Resultative counting and General knowledge ofnumbers. Each of the scales has 24 items spread over the eight parts.
